,Recommended,233230,29238639,Posted: 13 January,all,Wrath,"I have played this game twice now and I can safely say that I have absolutely no idea what happens in it or what it all means. I recommend it, but cannot point to any good reason why I should. It's strange, it's bizarre, and the entire experience is essentially ""what kind of video game would I make if I were only allowed to code while blazed?"" I'm relatively certain that the game is an exploration of the remains of a community on another world, but it definitely plays a lot better as an exercise in navigating someone's LSD-riddled subconscious. Because, as far as I can tell half of the time you stare at the screen going ""What."", there is actually no right answer.You progress by completing a number of puzzles and some of those can be tricky because there are times that it isn't immediately obvious that what you are looking at even is a puzzle, let alone what it expects you to do. You can ask the computer to give you up to three hints with various degrees of obviousness in order to solve the puzzles; however, in a number of rooms after spending ten minutes going ""what in the world am I doing"" or ""this is impossible"", you can press the hint buttons which will tell you ""actually, this room does nothing at all and you're just wasting your time"".So, after a while, I don't know, you can just relax and slip into ""ah, yes, another screwy thing in this dude's crumbling mind, of course it doesn't make sense, of course I have no idea what's going on"". This game is a mental prison and you have to escape the prison. If you want 2-4 hours of going ""wtf is this - wtf is that"" then it's for you, but don't expect much."
