,Recommended,233230,27898529,"Posted: 27 November, 2016",all,AzoreanEve,"I thoroughly enjoyed this more than I anticipated.Kairo needs you figure out the mechanic for each puzzle, unlike many other puzzle platformers, where a mechanic is introduced in the beginning and the game revolves around that mechanic (like Portal and the portal gun, Antichamber and the cube gun, etc).Here you don't need to learn anything, there's no tutorial section or equipment to obtain. Every puzzle is solved by moving about and going to the right place, sometimes at the right time.Visually, the graphics are simple, Very simple. The grain filter (optional) makes them look even grittier. This felt fitting to the scenery and theme of the game, especially when coupled with the soundtrack. However, keep in mind that when you set the FOV higher than default, the camera will clip through walls.The game is short. You can 100% it in a couple of hours if you don't loiter around and are fast at the puzzles. There's no actual story told to you, but you do see some things that give you substance for speculation on what is going on in this world.Oh and Kairo has number stations scattered around! Transmitting!"
,Not Recommended,233230,28287893,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,Vortiene,"Exploring the giant empty rooms is not hugely fun or engaging in the end. Is there a story? Is there any reason for me to care about it? After finishing the game, I don't really know. There are plenty of puzzles, most of them very very straightforward, where the harder ones are usually hard due to jankiness, such as aligning something based on your X/Y axis movements. The puzzle solving elements are OK, mediocre at best. One of the puzzles was, not even lying, 'press this button repeatedly until RNG decides you can solve the puzzle.' That's a bit lazy.The environments are interestingly designed and laid out, but usually very empty, and monochromatic. It's a stretch to call ""make some shapes in unity and instead of designing interesting textures just make everything monochrome and overlay a grain effect"" stylish. If you set your field of view higher than 60 degrees (the default), you can see through walls. It seems like this game just barely functions as intended. The graphical complexity is very very low as well.It's around 2-3 hours long, depending on whether you get stuck on puzzles. The soundtrack repeats often, changing between tracks in most rooms. Approximately 30% of the game is spent walking across large expanses that do not stay interesting to look at for that entire time spent walking.If you're the artsy type, it's possible that you'll enjoy this game. If you are into puzzle solvers, there are many better options. This game approaches being a walking simulator due to the large amount of walking to the next area in comparison with puzzle solving."
