,Recommended,233230,24912430,"Posted: 14 August, 2016",all,TheQuantumTantrum,"I really do enjoy my first person puzzle games, and that is exactly what Kairo is. Though Kairo is missing a neat mechanic that other more famous first person puzzle games have, it does have very clever puzzles in a fantastic geometric environment. Though some may argue that Kairo is a walking simulator, I would say that it is more than that.Now, as with many puzzle games, the difficulty curve is very important. Kairo does not hold your hand through play, but it does give you some idea on what to do. The curve is very good, as the difficulty does ramp up slightly while the puzzles become more interesting. However, there is one puzzle that is based around your position on a platform which, personally, I had to look up a solution as it was very difficult to understand. Other than that, the game succeeds in having very good puzzles in a gorgeous environment.The soundtrack in nothing spectacular as it is just ambience, but there is no loop which is great. Story is non-existent, which is fine as you do not need a story for this type of game. There are easter eggs and other things to do after completion, which slightly increases the length of the game. In fact, there is really no major issue with the game, and I would suggest picking it up if you enjoy obscure puzzle games."
