,Recommended,233230,34453598,Posted: 23 August,all,Arias,"I'm gonna be the first to admit that I'm terrible at puzzles. I'm pretty sure that every puzzle game I've ever played had to be beaten using a guide. Therefore, I'm somewhat limited in what I have a right to say about Kairo. Which isn't all that bad, actually, because I still can't think of anything to say. I completed Kairo less than half an hour ago using a very well-written 100% guide here on Steam, and the experience has left me mostly speechless. So, what do I have to say about Kairo?Well, I guess I can start by describing the game. Your protagonist is not technically a character, just a nameless, formless entity which serves as your window into the world.In fact, as revealed by end of the game's third part and by one of its final secrets, only two other characters even exist in this world, neither of whom are named, and only one of whom you will meet.Kairo is not a game about characters. In the vein of a lot of walking simulators like Dear Esther, puzzle games like Submachine, and mixes of the two like The Witness, Kairo is a game about its world.So, what is there to say about the world of Kairo? It's blocky, first off. The world is constructed primarily from stretched, stacked, and overlapping cubes, with the occasional sphere or disc thrown in, with colored fog fade-out in the distance. As for the world itself, I can only think to call it desolate. Kairo's environments are extremely varied, both in size and comprehensibility, but they all stand a chance of alienating you, which is something I found prevalent in Kairo: Alienation. The world around you is made from very simple shapes, but organized together into incredibly complex architecture. Often, you will find yourself on small islands of terrain within vast voids, which of course can make you feel very small in comparison to the world around you. Add to that the idea that you are the only entity occupying this world at the moment, and isolation combines with scale to create an impression that you are not just small within this world, but utterly insignificant within it.That last part is a lie, however. You are not insignificant to this world. In fact, by solving its puzzles in some sort of ridiculous cosmic game, you will manipulate the great machines of Kairo to fulfill a purpose that may not actually seem clear until the very end. The puzzles in Kairo are, of course, the part I have the least right to comment on. As I am utterly terrible at puzzles, this really isn't a game I was able to play to its fullest. The game still does its best to make things accessible to people like me, however, through the hint system. In something like the style of the Professor Layton series, Kairo's puzzles operate on a three-hint system. The game menu provides a hint option, and in rooms containing a puzzle, that hint option offers you three click-to-reveal hints which progressively state what you're supposed to do in a certain room, and how to do it, more simply and directly with each hint. Of course, as most games of its type do, Kairo sometimes offers up puzzles so complex or esoteric that even the guide I followed could only describe the solutions to the puzzles, and not the logic they follow.There are also secrets, of course. There are six runes within each of the three greater areas of the game, hidden in plain sight on the sides of columns or buildings so that you wouldn't ever see them by following the straight and narrow paths between portal doors and solving puzzles when you encounter them. Each greater area also contains a pedestal switch, which triggers a noticeable and often disorienting or unsettling shift in the immediate room, while also unlocking a very well-hidden door in a previous room in that greater area. Finally, each greater area has what's called a Vision Puzzle, which will not be solved through Hints and are most likely intended as a project for the player community to solve through examination and experimentation. Collecting all of these secrets in a single run of the game will unlock a small bonus area, containing few interesting easter eggs and a door leading to the secret ending, which is worth seeing for its sheer absurdity alone.Everything I just said should be taken with a grain of salt, though, since I did just say a whole lot about a game that I don't actually think there's a whole lot to say about. At the end of the day, I loved Kairo mostly for the experience. The alienation and isolation of the game's vast world create a feeling I personally enjoyed, and the tiny puzzle pieces of a story the game gives you are interesting enough to keep the theorists guessing for a while. And finally, since this is a game I don't really know what to say about, even after saying so much, I want to express that I'm not recommending this game to anyone. If you disliked things like Dear Esther or The Witness, I don't think you'll enjoy Kairo. I'm reccommending this game to people who read this review and others, understand what people who like this game think about it and like about it, and then think, ""Hey, I might like that too."""
,Recommended,233230,8232752,"Posted: 23 December, 2013",all,Rail,Beautiful
76561198045663266,Recommended,233230,31602875,Posted: 7 May,all,simonpeter,"Hauntingly beautiful, Kairo stuns with it's surreal and brutalist concrete vision of...?Others have remarked about a lack of meaning in this game, but I think it's there. It echoes through the vast alien chambers of this game, little glimpses of things recognisable. This feels like a monument to us, long after we're gone, made by *something* with a different kind of understanding of space.The puzzles are satisfying, without being too obtuse. The hint system is welcome, which I only found necessary for one puzzle that required an unreasonable leap of logic. There are apparently deeper puzzles to solve once finished, and  a number of collectables to find. Sadly, I have the patience for neither, although I did my best to hunt round the levels all I could.The visuals are striking in their simplicity, but are completely appropriate. The audio elevates the mood perfectly; it's utterly outstanding.I found the end strangely affecting, and the developer's final credit especially so.All in all, very much recommended."
