76561198072118811,Not Recommended,233230,10259546,"Posted: 27 May, 2014",all,littlefiredragon,"As much as I wanted to enjoy Kairo, I simply could not. There is nothing redeeming about it, in my opinion. The puzzles require extreme moon logic to figure out, and I managed to get through the game with no real understanding of what I was doing. I blindly stumbled through, hoping against hope that at some point, the confusion would clear up. It did not. I ended the game more confused than I started it, with a healthy helping of disappointment and bitterness to boot. Some may call the graphics abstract, unique, or elegantly minimalist; I call them lazy. They look unfinished and bland, as if the developers simply couldn't be bothered to polish them, and tried to pass this off as artistic choice. There are tantalizing hints of a story that never emerges, only a few little morsels here and there which, like a can containing only three potato chips, provides just enough taste to make you want more, only to be disappointed that you can't have any more. And no, the ending doesn't make anything clearer, or anything of that nature. If anything it'll just confuse you more. I sincerely regret spending my time and money on this game."
,Not Recommended,233230,28621928,"Posted: 24 December, 2016",all,Mr Owls,"The best puzzle games, imo, offer you some kind of simple principle which you are then obliged to apply in increasingly sophisticated ways to increasingly complex puzzles. You put 1+1 together, have a eureka! moment, and your brain is awash in dopamine. The Witness, Myst, Portal, and Fez are great examples of this.Kairo does not offer this. It's a run-around-until-you-bump-into-something-that-happens-to-solve-the-puzzle type game, and for that reason, I found it incredibly frustrating and tedious. There's no consistent logical principle behind the puzzles, so you can't take what you learned from the last one and apply it to a new one.Now, diverse puzzles with little consistent through-line wouldn't be that much of a problem, except there's no way to extract anything from the game's environment, either, as you would in say, Tomb Raider. The ''environmental exposition'' mentioned in the features seems rudimentary and not at all helpful. Because every room/level is the same flat, monochrome style, there's no suggestion that a certain block can be pushed, or anything like that. You have to wander around aimlessly in this bleak monochromatic world until you accidentally step or push something that happens to do something. And there's no compelling story elements from which you can derive why, and for what, you are doing this.To my mind, that defeats the purpose of solving a puzzle. If you're just wandering around for an hour until you bump into the right thing, it's not really ''solving''. It's just stumbling around. There's no rewarding feeling in ''solving'' something by accident. This could have been compensated for with a more developed aesthetic, or a more interesting story, even just an overarching theme that ties everything together. But those elements aren't there, or they're rudimentary at best."
