,Recommended,233230,11891499,"Posted: 27 August, 2014",all,DT76,"Kairo tries to be this atmospheric, mysterious puzzle/adventure game.  It partially succeeds, but is definitely not up to the standard of games from other series.The environments are fairy well done, and the static-y atmospheric effects make them feel appropriately ominous.  The trouble is, all these spooky monuments and inscrutable features seem mostly just thrown together.  I rarely got any sort of sense as to what they were supposed to have been.  The single biggest thing contributing to the lack of connection to the locations (aside from how sterile they all are) is the fact that all the doors connecting areas are teleporters.  You step through one and you're in an environment that looks nothing like the one you left; could be on the other side of the planet for all you know.  Most of these are just connecting corridors, with no purpose but to create a buffer between puzzle rooms.Nearly all the puzzles themselves were quite simple and solved quickly, save one which was very obtuse.  Some of them are supposed to be reactivating dormant machinery (except that the stuff is so abstract you have no idea what it's supposed todo), while others feel like puzzles for the sake of puzzles.You can breeze through the main sections in just a few hours.  Once you do, there are a couple of tougher puzzles that require hunting around for the proper code.  There's also this scavenger hunt thing where you try to find all the hidden glyphs around the rooms.  Neither feels all that interesting to me, since you're just going back over areas you've already visited and solved with a fine-tooth comb."
