,Recommended,233230,10646923,"Posted: 21 June, 2014",all,castorquinn,"In BriefKairois a narrative without words painting a picture of aloneness on a canvas made of staggeringly large geometry.Most valuable resource:The art.Of interest to:people who appreciate geometric abstraction, and like deeply mysterious Myst-style puzzlers.I have never before played a game with such an incredible feeling of scale.  The place is enigmatic, it is stunning but, more than anything else, it is *overpoweringly huge*.  Figuring out what you are supposed to be doing is part of the experience of this game, so don't be put off by what appears at the outset to be random acts of geometry.  There is meaning and purpose to this place; it just takes some time to start to piece it together.  This is a different kind of narrative.For me the strangest part of the experience of Kairo is that at the outset you are in a place of geometry and void, with no personality or sense of place; you are cast adrift with no instructions whatsoever, completely alone in a place which amplifies aloneness.  You aren't even sure what the game is, let alone what the game world is all about.  But by the end you feel like you know this place, you understand it, it is familiar and you are at home here - which, given the way the game ends, is the ultimate irony.There is a story here, but one told without words, and it is a magnificent story of great scale and great aloneness, and it is masterfully told."
