76561198030968100,Not Recommended,233230,14671753,"Posted: 26 February, 2015",all,crayolacannibal,"Summary:Interesting indie first-person puzzle game with terrible mechanics, its only redeeming quality is its unique atmosphere that is breathtaking modern art at times, but can be grating at others.Pros:Unique and thought provoking styling and ambianceUnique puzzles (some hard, others stupid easy)MinimalistGrand and wide open environmentsNostalgic 90s feel (at least to me)Cons:The intense color palette, sharp and grating sound effects, and an overall feeling of confusion makes the game interesting at first and then unpleasantMany of the puzzles are either confusing, super easy, or boringTerrible game engine (slow, buggy, see though walls and objects)Because the game is so grand and wide open you zoom around at 100mph across vast areas which is annoying at timesVery unpolishedFairly shortDetailed review:I played this game almost back-to-back withQbeh-1, a first-person puzzle game in the same vein. It was a funny coincidence because, in juxtaposition, these games couldn’t be further opposites. Qbeh-1 fosters a zen relaxed feeling with blue skies, cool water, open spaces, majestic buildings, relaxing ambient music, and a feeling of smooth progression using hands-on puzzles with standard building blocks. Kairo on the other hand is a strange game with a surreal, Stonehenge, modern abstract,David SmithCubifeeling with graphics reminiscent of the 90s era (reminded me of an old dos game called S.C.A.R.A.B.). It has an environment that is discomforting and disconcerting, trapping the player in dark psychedelic tombs and inorganic voids. The game uses harsh grating sound effects and music and surrounds the player with static filled screens, sharp abstract constructions, and bizarre features. There are no controls beyond the basic movement controls; every “action” is performed by stepping on tiles or otherwise bumping into the various features found within the giant rooms. Perfecting the feeling of being lost in an abstract void is a complete lack of storyline or instruction beyond a list of puzzle hints that can be found in the menu. In short, the game makes you feel like you’re traveling through the monolith from 2001: A Space Odyssey. It’s not bad, but I wouldn’t recommend it to just anyone as it would offend all but those who can appreciate a game that is little more than a virtual modern art gallery with simple puzzles separating each exhibit."
