,Recommended,233230,34047379,Posted: 5 August,all,Sheep!,"So, graphically,Kairoisn't much.  This sombre and moody atmosphere of monochromatic light and endless heavy stone-and-concrete textures with fog and film-grain effect isn't just part of some dark setpieces, it's a dreary and oppressive constant throughout the entire game.  The environments are not spooky-scary, just alien, megalithic and unwelcoming.  It makes the game a dark and tedious trudge through an uncaring place that's largely ambivalent to your presence.  You solve puzzle after puzzle to accomplish you're-not-sure-what just hoping that eventually you will emerge into sunshine and light, and it never really happens.Kairois one of those mysterious games that screams questions: ""Who am I? Where am I? What am I doing? Why am I here? What is the purpose of all this stuff?""  It never deigns to answer the question.  Thanks to some additional information from very well-hidden easter eggs and a second ending, fan forums have put together a reasonable theory that fits the observed facts, but it still has enormous gaps in it that have not and will never be answered.Kairois similar toThe Witnessin being an intelligent and mysterious puzzle-driven game that refuses to fully answer the questions it raises.  Quality-wise,Kairois significantly inferior toThe Witness, of course, but it's accordingly priced a lot lower. This can be a great experience, for those who accept from the outset that the game will be surreal and joyless, full of questions for which the answers are forever withheld.  It's like the game equivalent ofa Bergman film.  If you aren't turned off by that kind of solemn artistry, then you'll enjoy it.  It's definitely not a game for everybody, though."
