,Not Recommended,233230,32398482,Posted: 13 June,all,Nekogorgon the Omnipurrtent,"Bottomline: Minimalism does not and should not equal 'minimal effort'.First of all, I am aware this is a four year old game. Also, it's pretty cheap to request a €0,99 refund, I obviously don't care about the money. The developer just didn't put the required effort into the game, and therefore I do not wish to support.I bought the game because I was interested in the minimalist, brutalist artstyle of the game and I also have a taste for mystery and environmental puzzles. The developer however, appears to use the word 'minimalism' as an excuse to deliver a rushed game that is, bluntly put, really bad. Incoherent and even nonsensical game design is accompanied by lazy art (for example: symbols are created using text parentheses.)There are many high-quality minimalistic, abstract games out there in the world; Kairo isn't one of them. If you're going to make a minimalist, abstract 3D environment you should at least bother to do some proper lightbaking and do some research into light and space in general because this game was rife with visual artefacts.I understand the amount of time and effort that goes into game development, but I recommend spending five bucks on beers instead of this game.One positive point: I did like the atmospheric ambient music."
