,Recommended,233230,17408793,"Posted: 5 August, 2015",all,thelogicalghost,"IMPORTANT: When you hit the normal ending, wait for the credits to play out. They're not long.Pros:- Puzzles become interesting when you have no ""hand"" or ""activate"" controls. By limiting the player to mere movement controls, old puzzles feel fresh, and there's an extra sense of accomplishment with even fairly simple puzzles.- The environment's minimalist polygon theme manages, surprisingly, to stay varied, interesting, and even evokative throughout the game, contributing to the theme of ""strange and yet familiar"" that pervades.- Difficulty to normal end is low, difficulty to secret end is high.- No penalty for exploration, experimentation, or taking your time.- Overall, definitely enjoyable.Cons:- The ""story"" aspect is a little too vague. You paid $5, folks, this ain't Myst or Portal. While there are enough ""clues"" that a player can vaguely put together a plot (and considerably more blatant clues as rewards for solving secret puzzles), there's plenty that's just left to imagination.- The mechanic that resets you to a safe ledge can glitch considerably, leaving you in a fall-to-your-death loop, though this can be solved by exiting the game and reloading.- One of the final secret puzzles is actually impossible to solve on your own. Your game will have 1/5 of the solution, and which fifth is chosen at random. So you're either going to need lots of friends, or cheat and look at a walkthrough.Final Note: Don't take my playtime as a good guide to the runthrough time of this game. I got irritated and consulted a walkthrough for two of the secret puzzles and half the rune locations."
