76561197993492300,Recommended,233230,11277446,"Posted: 16 July, 2014",all,Scotty Firebird,"Kairo is a beautiful game. It stands right up there with best artistic endeavors in gaming in the last ten years, and its tone is perfectly executed. Do not play this game in a room full of housemates screaming at League of Legends (as I did in my first attempt); in order to appreciate the mood, you should be alone and open to anything. Because, thought the game does not literally deliver EVERYTHING, it conveys the feeling that it COULD, and that is a mostly lost art in gaming, as well as literature and film. After fully completing every aspect of the game, I still am not entirely sure of the exact story narrative, and the writer in me hates that, but that same writer also appreciates it. How easy would it have been for the developer to just give us computer terminals and characters to explain everything? But that's why this is so great. It felt like I was really there, really trying to piece together something entirely on my own. If I were actually there, I doubt there'd be notes scattered about just telling me every detail about what happened. But the story, while integral to the setting in design, is not essential to experiencing the setting. I highly recommend this to people who loved Myst back in the day; who enjoy newer exploration-based environmental games like FEZ and Gone Home; those of you who have to be driven by saving the princess and killing the bad guys, however, might want to sit this one out. But I enjoyed this game immensely. Thumbs way up!"
